The paper focuses on improving the performance of a robot in stacking and nesting objects, which falls under the category of robotics (cs.RO). The use of RGB-D cameras and image processing techniques to detect success suggests that computer vision (cs.CV) is also relevant. The paper also discusses the use of language expressions to encode object information, which suggests that natural language processing (cs.CL) may be relevant. The use of machine learning techniques to train a model to reason about success detection suggests that artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG) are also relevant. Finally, the paper discusses the potential applications of the research in tasks such as clearing a dining table, which suggests that human-computer interaction (cs.HC) may also be relevant.
